    <item>
      <title>JACT Reading Greek 7F Translation</title>
      <link>https://justinhayes.me/post/jact-reading-greek-7f-translation/</link>
      <pubDate>Sat, 13 Jul 2019 11:44:00 -0400</pubDate>
      
      <guid>https://justinhayes.me/post/jact-reading-greek-7f-translation/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;When Euthydemos concludes his argument, Dionysodorus makes the case for the contradiction. Sophists were infamous by Socrates&amp;rsquo; day for making both sides of an argument appear equally valid.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>JACT Reading Greek 7E Translation</title>
      <link>https://justinhayes.me/post/jact-reading-greek-7e-translation/</link>
      <pubDate>Fri, 12 Jul 2019 12:37:31 -0400</pubDate>
      
      <guid>https://justinhayes.me/post/jact-reading-greek-7e-translation/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Continuing the dialogue, Euthydemos leads Kleinias to contradict his previous statement that the clever are the ones who learn, not the ignorant.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>JACT Reading Greek 7D Translation</title>
      <link>https://justinhayes.me/post/jact-reading-greek-7d-translation/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 11 Jul 2019 07:13:31 -0400</pubDate>
      
      <guid>https://justinhayes.me/post/jact-reading-greek-7d-translation/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Socrates goes to the Lyceum and finds two sophists, Euthydemos and Dionysodoros, speaking among those assembled. He volunteers one of his young students, Kleinias, to engage the sophists in philosophical dialogue.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    
